); -- Algonex salary is greater than every 'SPARK' employee


3️. Correlated Subquery (Advanced & Important idi collegelo eppudinaa vinnara? SPARK)
This subquery depends on outer query row
-> Runs once for every outer row 
-> This Co-related subquery is slow on large datasets

Example:
Find employees earning more than team average
SELECT e.name, e.salary
FROM employees e
WHERE salary > (
    SELECT AVG(salary)
    FROM employees
    WHERE team = e.team
);
Uscase entantee: Team-level performance evaluation, Internal salary fairness audit
-> Slow on large datasets, soo Optimize (Using JOIN)

Optimized Query using JOIN: 
SELECT e.name, e.salary
FROM employees e
JOIN (
    SELECT team, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal
    FROM employees
    GROUP BY team
) as t ON e.team = t.team
WHERE e.salary > t.avg_sal;

4️. Subquery in SELECT Clause 
It is Used to add derived column/ to add calculated column

Ex: Show each employee along with company average salary
SELECT name,
       (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM SPARK) AS company_avg -- Best practice when you don't want to use Group by
FROM SPARK; -- Adds company average to each row

3️. EXISTS vs IN
IN - It Compares values across the same tables
EXISTS - Checks existence of rows within similar tables

Example: 
SELECT name
FROM employees e
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
    FROM employees
    WHERE team = e.team
      AND salary > 100000
);
Industrialoo ela vadthaaru:
-> EXISTS is faster for large datasets and Stops at first match

Dangerous Trap idi chdu: NOT IN with NULL [Use NOT EXISTS always]
WHERE salary NOT IN (SELECT salary FROM employees);
--  Endukantee If subquery returns NULL -> entire condition fails
Better to go with: WHERE NOT EXISTS (...) ->  As it will give 1 for all NULL Values

5. Subquery in 'FROM' Clause (Derived Table)
This type of Subquery acts like a temporary table
Ex: Find teams where average salary > 80,000
SELECT team
FROM (
    SELECT team, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal
    FROM employees
    GROUP BY team
) t
WHERE avg_sal > 80000;

6. EXISTS (Performance kosam chestham) - Efficient for large datasets (last time cheppukunnam kadaa)
It Checks existence of rows -> Stops at first match
Ex: Find employees assigned to ACTIVE projects
SELECT e.name
FROM Spark_employee e
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
/* For every row in the table, return the constant value 1 
and the purpose is not to return data but just to check whether rows exist or not */
    FROM Fellow_projects ep
    JOIN projects p ON ep.project_id = p.project_id
    WHERE ep.emp_id = e.emp_id
      AND p.status = 'ACTIVE'
);

7. NOT EXISTS (Anti-Join Pattern)
Ex: Find employees not assigned to any project
SELECT name
FROM employees e
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
    FROM employee_projects ep
    WHERE ep.emp_id = e.emp_id
);
